                        oscillates between 
                        1 and 2, compares 3 
                        and 5 with 1 and 2, 
                        and, finally, also 
                        compares 4. Base, 
                        middle
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Fourth example</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson7_fig27" type="explanation"></figure>
                    <p>Formal statement:</p>
                    <p>Formation: stable<seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureS"></figure></seg></p>
                    <p>
                        Functions: Arrangement: diagonal<seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureT"></figure></seg>
                        Articulation: rigid<seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureU"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p> Development: increase and decrease<seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureV"></figure></seg></p>
                    <p> 
                        Direction of increase: from
                        outside to inside<seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureW"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> Receptive function:</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson7_fig28"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The principal weight, 1, catches the beholder's 
                        eye to a marked degree, because this principal 
                        weight is also located at the most important place; 
                        then the eye oscillates back and forth as it circles 
                        around towards the four 2s and then oscillates 
                        around in a new circle towards the four 3s.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We learn: The movement-function of a work need not 
                        be emphasized as such. For as you have seen, the most 
                        quiescent and stable work is also movement.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Nevertheless, the question as to the nature of 
                        actual movement-forms, actually dynamic formation, 
                        is very much alive. This can lead us to new, richer 
                        formal domains.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Monday, March 13, exercise:</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        I: Pasture of the  
                        grazing animal
                        Functions of this part
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        II: Range of the  
                        hunting animal
                        Functions of the other 
                        part
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureX"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureY"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureZ"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson7_figureAA"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson7_figureAB"></figure>
                    <p>
                        III: Possible combination of I and II, leading to 
                        the subordination of one character or to the 
                        equal ranking of the two.
                    </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson8">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="number8"></figure></seg>Monday, March 20, 1922
                    </p>  
                    <p>
                        The function of a visual work is the way in which 
                        the work's construction, set in motion over time,
                        communicates itself to the eye and the way in which 
                        the character of movement inherent in each work is 
                        imposed upon the eye and upon the powers of reception 
                        lying behind it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here we touch upon the old story of effect, 
                        but through emphasis on the character of movement 
                        inherent in each visual work, not the effect 
                        generally, the effect per se, but the kind of effect 
                        particular to each case.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To differentiate these kinds of effects by classi- 
                        fying them amounts to classifying the types of works.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        As we saw last time, every work, even 
                        the most concise, moves within time both as it 
                        emerges (productively) and as it is apprehended 
                        (receptively). Our eye is constructed in such a 
                        way that it scans, over time, all that we perceive 
                        visually.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The eye, wearied of familiar nature or 
                        familiar culture, steers towards new, stimulating 
                        peculiarities. Should it fall to a visual work to 
                        exert such stimuli, then the eye steers towards that 
                        area where, as the greatest force of attraction, 
                        the strongest unfolding of pictorial energy asserts 
                        itself.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Such a stimulus is always of a relative 
                        nature. If, on a white plane× that has made the 
                        eye curious, an especially deep black is produced 
                        somewhere, then this black in comparison with that 
                        white is a quite strong energy.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or when on a green plane enticing closer
                        examination,
                    </p>
                    <p> × my sheet of paper on the blackboard</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        a sharply contrasting red asserts itself, then this 
                        time the red is the special energy. The same applies 
                        to white on black, warm on cool, lively on calm, and 
                        vice versa, higher on lower, stronger on weaker, 
                        harder on softer. Or active on static, and all the 
                        other opposites that, once created, have the power 
                        to wrest the eye towards themselves.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        With the feeling (which was somewhat reinforced 
                        by the last exercise), with the feeling, that the 
                        explanations from last time were not yet clear 
                        enough, and in order to be able to build more 
                        securely on them, I am going to backtrack a little.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        To demonstrate again for you how both the product 
                        and the recept move in time, I will choose as my 
                        product the most concise construct that cannot emerge 
                        at a single stroke (not even one produced with single 
                        strokes from each of two hands at once):  
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig1"></figure>
                    <p>
                        A construct that consists of the factors "first," 
                        "second," and "third." This product was not created 
                        in a single stroke but rather took its time; nor
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        indeed can it be assimilated in a single moment either, 
                        despite its truly marked concision. Rather: 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The stimulated eye jumps to the strongest energy, 
                        to "first,"
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_figureA"></figure>
                    <p>compares it with "second"</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureB"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>and with "third,"
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="center"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig2"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        (Recept of
                        fig. 1)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        which again means a succession or a temporal movement. 
                        Here the reception image or, in short, the recept, 
                        presents the function of the product (fig. 1). 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We now have before us: there (fig. 1), a planar 
                        image as the product and, here, a linear image as the 
                        recept.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureC"></figure></seg>
                        Note
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureD"></figure></seg> There [fig. 1] the planes are to be thought of as 
                        active planes and here [fig. 2] as active lines, which are 
                        not (mind you!) mutually dependent on one another in the way 
                        they were represented earlier, i.e., as here: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureF"></figure></seg> where the 
                        passive lines depend on the active plane, or here: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureG"></figure></seg> where 
                        the plane, as opposed to the lines, is the result and is 
                        therefore passive. 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureE"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Therefore: there, active planes and, here, active lines 
                        that are functionally linked with each other.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Closer examination of the reception image reveals a 
                        movement gradually retreating from the base of the 
                        force, or a gradually weaker valuation compared with 
                        the fundamental principal value. Sequential order and 
                        ranking order coincide. 
                    </p> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig3"></figure>
                    <p>
                        These red forms of diminishing force are the expression  
                        of the function of the three values of our production 
                        image (fig. 1). At the same time, the new form is 
                        itself again an image and indeed an image with pure 
                        movement-form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We will make this last experience even clearer yet 
                        with a new product.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig4"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This new product consists of nine graded values that, for sim-  
                        plicity's sake, I represent only with quantitative differences. 
                        Language and function would of course find even more vivid 
                        expression with gradations based on tone value or color value. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For the purpose of configuring the reception, the 
                        centric character of this product leads me to schematize the 
                        gradation of values in the form of nine circles that recede 
                        further and further from the center. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig5"></figure></seg>The diagonals may also be considered.
                        And, with that, the schema in which  
                        the action of reception is to be played  
                        out has been prepared.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Before approaching the product, let us envision the 
                        following little prelude: We have moved about, getting 
                        our exercise for some time in the countryside and are 
                        satisfied and tired after our plein-air impressions, 
                        so that coming back into the dark house feels like a 
                        relief. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The room in which we now find ourselves is 
                        completely black, empty and black. The next room that we 
                        enter is also black with the exception of one painted 
                        wall.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here our thoroughly stimulated eye now pounces on 
                        the pure white note, which I have labeled "first." Then 
                        to the still very light note labeled "second," and next 
                        it proceeds to the remaining values, in increasingly 
                        darker gradations.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig6"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Thus, the path via the separate stimulus-points arranges 
                        itself in the form of a spiral around the white in the 
                        center. The stimulus-points recede ever further from the 
                        center, while maintaining their relatedness to it.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig7"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The product (fig. 4) consisted of solemnly stable and 
                        quiescent forms. Its recept, the function of this stably 
                        formed construct, is the purest movement-form conceivable, a 
                        spiral. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And so, with every further attempt to represent the 
                        functions of a visual work, we will obtain movement-forms 
                        again and again; the further we advance towards the essence 
                        of the function, the purer the movement-forms.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig8"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This new product shows, in contrast to before, a now 
                        more erratic arrangement of the values. The preceding 
                        pastorale of the grazing cattle has become the range of 
                        the hunting predator, as will be clearly shown in the 
                        corresponding form of the function.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        As the first schema to represent this function, to start 
                        with I choose a more epic system (to be read from left 
                        to right) and note on it the values corresponding to the 
                        leaps in value in the product, not in order of rank, but 
                        from bottom to top in the sequence third, fourth, eighth, 
                        ninth, First, fifth, seventh, sixth, second, in which the 
                        particular position of the One at middle height should be 
                        kept in mind. Ranking order and sequential order are not 
                        identical.                    
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig9"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="center"/>
                        For the second schema, I 
                        choose one that is more 
                        dramatic, with high values 
                        in the middle, therefore 
                        one organized centrally, 
                        and I group values in the 
                        product according to their 
                        proximity to the center: 
                        first (center), eighth, 
                        fifth, ninth, fourth, 
                        seventh, sixth, third, and 
                        second
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig10"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In both schemata, I put the notes in the places that correspond 
                        to the positions of values in the product, and, by connecting 
                        according to rank, I obtain two different recepts that 
                        naturally resemble each other internally to a hair. 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig11"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig12"></figure> 
                    <p>
                        Having arrived at the dynamic form, we first 
                        want to make a slight distinction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The movement of a formal element that leads to the 
                        creation of a new formal element need not also produce 
                        a dynamic form. The movement of a point into the mathe
                        matical straight line <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureH"></figure></seg>is
                        indeed a movement-action but not a movement-form. This 
                        same line, if it is then pushed to produce a plane, is 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureI"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        not a dynamic line because it 
                        is no longer a line at all but 
                        a plane. However, even the
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        plane thus generated (through the line's movement-action) 
                        still need not present a dynamic character as a plane.
                        A visible state of dynamism first arises from gradual 
                        growth or diminution with regard to the quantity or 
                        quality of the energy applied.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        You will recall the role of the weighing scales,
                        when we were still stable and static and were weighing 
                        the values against each other on either side. What are the 
                        scales to us now in the measurement of dynamic values? 
                        How shall we weigh things that don't keep still?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But perhaps the following bit of imagining has something 
                        calming in itself:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig13"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This little building is supposed to stand on very small 
                        feet! That won't be very easy. So get the scales over 
                        here, and make that the gold-weighing scales. The weights 
                        tally up: 4 + 1 = 2 + 3. But in practice the thing still 
                        looks rather dubious.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        What to do? Let us empathize with it--we who, after 
                        all, are ourselves buildings standing on small feet 
                        and who must not fall down. What do we do in order 
                        not to fall? What do we do when we have not succeeded 
                        in establishing the calm of stasis through a counter
                        balancing shift (on a small scale) of our weighted parts?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First we move a leg (enlargement of the base) and 
                        perhaps the other soon afterwards. And finally we walk; 
                        that makes balancing easier.
                    </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>We have become a dynamic form and sense relief.</p>
                    <p>
                        And our little building on a small foot? It can't 
                        walk, can it?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It can't walk but perhaps another kind of movement 
                        suits it.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let's not enlarge its base but, instead, let us 
                        place it on a point and set it swinging vigorously in 
                        motion about itself.  
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig14"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Then it's called a top, the top that every child knows 
                        does not fall as long as the motion lasts, as long as 
                        the top spins. Just as calming for us can be a rolling 
                        wheel, the boy's hoop, or even the spinning diabolo, 
                        which understands the art of dancing on the high wire.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig15"></figure>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig16"></figure>
                    <p>
                        With in principle such calming thoughts,  we will keep 
                        looking for a replacement for the now  "obsolete" 
                        weighing scales. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The pendulum is a very ingenious   little instrument 
                        consisting of a small lead weight, w, and a line, 
                        which swings back and forth from a fixed point, p, 
                        the center; the line, as radius, moves with the weight.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The concept of back and forth is essential here, 
                        i.e., the property of the pendulum that consists in 
                        immediately describing the corresponding counter
                        motion to each motion.
                    </p> 
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig17a"></figure>
                        <cb n="center"/><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig17b"></figure>
                        <cb n="right"/><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig17c"></figure>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        This one case of the compensatory unification of 
                        motion and counter-motion is, however, not the only 
                        possibility. We can think of a less machine-like 
                        handling, even a very sensitive manual one. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let us take a very long line × and guide the weight with 
                        appreciable slackness.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        Handled this way, 
                        the lead describes 
                        both motion and 
                        counter-motion 
                        independently.
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig18"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>× one of Mélisande's hairs</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        We can proceed yet further from the slackened manual 
                        handling to the sentimental journey of the central 
                        point, p, and the pendulum-script will become the 
                        transcribed expression of the particular form of that 
                        journey.  
                    </p> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig19"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Here, for example, the pendulum-script is the dynamic 
                        expression of the vertical straight line, and we arrive 
                        at a dynamic variation on the static construction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Furthermore, we could guide the straight form of 
                        the journey dynamically, along a meandering path, or we 
                        could wander in any form we like.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or we could complete the slackening of the line 
                        at the right moment by letting it go, and the pendulum 
                        becomes a gentle sling, writing in this way, and, like 
                        the counter-motions of the fixed pendulum, the slingshot 
                        counter-motion is easy to understand and complete.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        However, a new phenomenon occurs if, once more allowing 
                        the pendulum to swing quite calmly to and fro, we think 
                        of the force of gravity being abolished suddenly in the 
                        middle of an oscillation (fig. 20), or if we lend the 
                        swing so much force that gravity is defeated.   
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        In this way, with the pendulum no longer bound to the 
                        earth, the cosmic movement-form suddenly arises:
                    </p>
                    <p>The pendulum swings around in a circle.</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig20"></figure>
                    <p>
                        In this closed, endless motion the need for a counter
                        motion ceases, and indeed the pendulum renounces the 
                        counter-motion in the new circumstances. 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_fig21"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        As opposed to the previous force, which I called 
                        the force of gravity, we now become acquainted with a 
                        new force that I call centrifugal force.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        New journeys are conceivable with the circling 
                        pendulum, too, if the center is set in motion or 
                        if movement starts with the radius being either 
                        lengthened, upon which ever wider circles sweep out, or 
                        shortened, upon which the circles grow ever tighter, 
                        until the lovely spectacle dies with a jerk, in the 
                        point.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig22"></figure>
                        <cb n="right"/><figure xml:id="lesson8_fig22a"></figure>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        The latter is the story of the spiral. Its movement 
                        is no longer endless, inherently quiescent, and so 
                        the question of direction of motion is raised. We must 
                        know this direction because the question dependent on 
                        the lengthening or shortening of the radius (fig. 22a) 
                        is essentially psychic. It runs: Do I loosen myself 
                        from the center in ever freer movement? Or will my
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        movements become more and more bound to a center until 
                        it finally swallows me whole?
                    </p> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureJ"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureK"></figure></seg>
                        motion of the radius 
                        away from C   
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureL"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson8_figureM"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        motion of the
                        radius towards C
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is nothing less than the question of life and 
                        death. And the little arrow makes the decision.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Monday, March 27, 1922</p> 
                    <p>
                        Movement exercise: "The Fountain," not the appearance 
                        of the fountain but the essence of the fountain, the 
                        forces of the water as arrangement and above all as 
                        dynamic functioning. 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson8_figureN"></figure>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson9">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="number9"></figure></seg>Monday, April 3, 1922
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The arrow is a projectile precisely formed with 
                        regard to duration and direction of force. Even the 
                        simplest weapon is seized out of the need to extend 
                        our limited physical reach, e.g., the cudgel, 
                        which extends the arm and increases the force of 
                        its swing, leading to firm contact with the target 
                        and fulfilling the will to reach this out-of-range 
                        target without loss of time or other advantages. 
                        From the place just where I stand, without going up 
                        close, with the cudgel I can hit a target that I 
                        couldn't have reached without a weapon.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A cast stone is an even more effective device in 
                        this respect. It hits its target while obviating 
                        the need for direct, firm contact; it arrives 
                        through the air at the object over there. In order 
                        to reach this object with some effectiveness, it 
                        needs force and direction during its brief journey: 
                        direction up to the point of contact, and force 
                        over and above.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig1"></figure>
                    <p> Not so much the less than precise accuracy as chiefly the</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        excessive effort required in throwing led to the 
                        perfection of the handling of projectiles.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Beyond a doubt such perfection in the sense of 
                        energy reduction led to the invention of the sling.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I remember as boys we would cut hazel switches 
                        and then get ourselves some "missiles" out of the 
                        nearby potato field. We speared these missiles in the 
                        form of potatoes firmly onto the thin sticks and set 
                        the apparatus going centrifugally, increasing the 
                        impetus to the point where the missile loosed itself 
                        from the switch.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig2"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The effect was of course astonishingly great. We did 
                        not need to make complete swings of the arm as when 
                        throwing the stone; this work was taken over from us 
                        for the most part by the sling. Instead, energetic 
                        movements of the wrist, briefly involving the forearm 
                        at the very end, were enough.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       The considerable energy saved was an evident 
                        improvement, for the potato whizzed over several 
                        houses, much farther than ten or twenty carefully 
                        aimed stone-throws put together. And one remained 
                        quite fresh. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But the accuracy remained questionable, and we 
                        secretly admired the achievement of the shepherd 
                        David, who hit Goliath in the middle of his 
                        undoubtedly not very big forehead.
                    </p>
                    <p> The accuracy was therefore not only in need of </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        correction but also capable of being corrected. We made 
                        this discovery en route to the elastic slingshot.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This time we cut forked branches from the thicket
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureA"></figure></seg> 
                        and attached highly stretchable rubber bands to the ends
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_fig3"></figure></seg>
                        of the fork; when fired, the bands gave the projectile 
                        no less force and allowed its direction to be controlled. 
                        Accuracy was also increased by changing the missile from 
                        a stone to a kind of arrow, which one could fashion out 
                        of a hairpin. <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureB"></figure></seg> 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_fig4"></figure></seg> 
                         <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureC"></figure></seg> 
                        A little pennant made of colored wool served as a 
                        rudder and for grasping and also as decoration.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Related to this was the bow and arrow, which, of 
                        course, we also made diligent use of.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig5"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Reduction of the energy required and improvement of 
                        aim were achieved. Both factors decisively influenced 
                        not only the whole little gadget but also the shaping 
                        of the projectile, which, first of all because of its 
                        length, experienced little friction and then, because 
                        it was long and straight, made aiming considerably 
                        easier and maintained the chosen direction as well. 
                        Voilà the arrow: the
                        arrow as shaft, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureD"></figure></seg>
                        tip, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureE"></figure></seg>
                        and rudder: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureF"></figure></seg>
                    </p>  
                    <p>
                        The bow and arrow, with a sighting mechanism for 
                        the final perfecting of accuracy and with a mechanism 
                        for holding the drawn string and a trigger, is called 
                        a crossbow. One's body is relieved of all possible 
                        strain, enabling concentration on aiming.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        William Tell's shot at the apple only has its 
                        meaning because a psychological complication was 
                        linked to it. It would have been easy to hit the mark 
                        with this superior instrument were it not for this 
                        shock to the soul.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The modern firearm, for its part, harks all the 
                        way back to the blowgun, with which every boy is also 
                        familiar. But as regards the arrow, which is here 
                        atavistically still called the ball, the modern 
                        firearm brings in an essential novelty: its two
                        dimensional movement.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig6"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The dynamic rifling inside the gun barrel imparts a 
                        rotational movement to the bullet racing through.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        One could call this modern projectile a screwing 
                        arrow, or drilling arrow, because this two-dimensional 
                        forward movement is reminiscent of screws and drills.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (Note: The movement of large steamships and torpedoes 
                        is based on this principle.)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The father of all mobile or thrown projectiles, so 
                        also of the arrow, was the thought: How can I extend 
                        my reach to over there? Across that river, that lake? 
                        Over that mountain?
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureG"></figure></seg>
                        To over there?
                        Common to this father and to all of his sons are both 
                        the linearity of the movement and the length of its path 
                        in relation to the body of the projectile.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The father is all spirit, all idea, indeed all thought. 
                        His movement can be mathematically straight, unaffected 
                        by obstacles, frictionless because bodiless, unrestricted 
                        as to length, finite or infinite.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This capacity of human beings to traverse the earthly 
                        and celestial realms at will by means of the mind, in 
                        contrast to their physical powerlessness, is the original 
                        human tragedy. The tragedy of the mind.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The consequence of this simultaneous powerlessness 
                        of the body and simultaneous mobility of the mind is 
                        the dichotomy of human existence. Half-shackled, half
                        winged: each of the two parts, through the perception of 
                        its counterpart, becomes conscious of the tragedy of its 
                        halfness.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig7"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The farther the journey from here to there, the heavier 
                        the tragedy. It is certainly founded, however, on the 
                        very fact of the point of departure, on the necessity 
                        of having to free oneself from a constraint, of having 
                        to become movement and of not being movement already. 
                        So the tragedy is there in the beginning.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The trajectory responds to: How does the arrow 
                        overcome frictional drag? Will the movement continue 
                        (till over there, where under no circumstances will 
                        it become infinite), but at least till over there? A 
                        little farther than usual! Than possible?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        &lt;In parentheses: So, arrows! Give yourselves wings so 
                        you don't tire all too early. Let yourselves be shaped 
                        so as to hit your mark, so you reach your trajectory's 
                        end, lest your own end be to lead nowhere!&gt;
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       shaft: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureJ"></figure></seg>
                        tip: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureK"></figure></seg>
                        rudder: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureL"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A genuine African arrow consists of shaft, tip, and 
                        rudder, like so. The tip must not only cut through 
                        the air as sharply as possible but also pierce the 
                        target as deeply as possible and stick there as firmly 
                        as possible by means of barbs.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The rudder of such an arrow serves to reinforce the 
                        direction of the shaft and make maintaining the flight 
                        path easier.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Our symbolic arrow differs to some extent from the 
                        African arrow. The concept "path" applies here to the 
                        shaft, and the concept "steering of the tip" applies to 
                        the tip, whereby the rudder on the end of the African 
                        arrow becomes redundant.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        Our arrow thus looks like this: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureM"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Equal length of the lines of the tip and equal 
                        angles between each line and the horizontal shaft result 
                        in a horizontal path.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig8"></figure>
                    <p>
                        fig. 8 [Given that: lengths a = b
                        angles  α = β   
                        : result in horizontal
                        path, c]   
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Unequal length and angle of the lines of the tip 
                        result in a path that curves up or down.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig9"></figure>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig10"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This is grounded on the rule of the parallelogram of 
                        forces and manifests itself quite nicely in its one part 
                        that refers to direction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Two cooperating forces a and b, pointing in different 
                        directions, result in a new force c, which proves to 
                        be the diagonal of the parallelogram formed by the two 
                        forces a and b.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        So: If both tip-rudder forces are equal in relation 
                        to the horizontal, the path remains horizontal.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If both tip-rudder forces are unequal in relation 
                        to the horizontal, the path is turned aside by the 
                        tip-rudder force that exhibits the greater deviation 
                        from the horizontal.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig11"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The stronger the upward-steering force, the higher 
                        the path climbs; the stronger the downward-steering 
                        force, the more the path falls; and in earthly reality 
                        this latter case will always arise after a certain 
                        time, when the earth's force of attraction, with a 
                        gradual drop in speed resulting from drag or friction, 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        confers more and more predominance on the downward
                        steering force.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig12"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Thus the earthly curve presents itself as finite 
                        movement,
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig13"></figure>
                    <p>
                        where the end, in practice, is on the earth's 
                        surface but theoretically at the center of the 
                        sphere of the earth,
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_fig14"></figure></seg>and in contrast to this, the cosmic curve, which 
                        withdraws from the 
                        earth, presents itself 
                        as infinite movement, 
                        i.e., inasmuch as it 
                        turns into a circle 
                        or at least into an 
                        ellipse.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Even at these heights developments are still 
                        conceivable, even if one knows nothing of the dynamic 
                        paths of the stars.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        One can think of such a circling as an increasing 
                        screw motion,
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig15"></figure>
                    <p>
                        which, when projected flat, is converted into the 
                        motion-positive spiral.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig16"></figure>
                    <p>
                        If, however, one thinks conversely of a circling 
                        star approaching another, stronger star too closely, 
                        so that its orbit is drawn ever tighter, then we 
                        arrive symbolically at the motion-antagonistic 
                        spiral, the death-spiral, in which the curve of 
                        the movement becomes tighter and tighter, which 
                        perilously leads to nothingness.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The perilous aspect of this mental image is 
                        the alarming rhythmic acceleration towards the end. 
                        With the steering of the arrow, the concentric side 
                        heads more and more towards catastrophe.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig17"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Anyone who wants to experience this should imagine 
                        rolling like a ball inside a funnel under centrifugal 
                        force in ever tighter curves and in ever accelerating 
                        rhythms towards the bottom of the funnel, towards the 
                        dead center.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        No rescue; unless a door opens somewhere, 
                        unless somewhere a new force of a repelling or 
                        attracting nature makes itself felt, as here:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig18"></figure>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig19"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        as here where through the arrival of a new force the 
                        prevalence of the concentric steering is superseded 
                        by the prevalence of the eccentric. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Holding this process in our mind's eye, we 
                        proceed from the symbol to the compositional schema:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig20"></figure>
                    <p>
                        As you see, I distinguish between cause and 
                        effect. Analytically, I schematize the concentric 
                        forces, A1 and A2, and the eccentric force, B, as 
                        causes; and, synthetically, I schematize the motion
                        negative spiral as effect A, with its emergency exit 
                        as effect B.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I must begin by saying that considered by 
                        itself, in minimal terms, the arrow was already in 
                        itself a synthesis of cause and effect. The two side
                        rudders, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureN"></figure></seg>  or the two sides of the parallelogram 
                        of the direction of forces, could  
                        be considered directional causes,
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        the resultant diagonal of the parallelogram of the 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureO"></figure></seg> direction of forces could be seen as 
                        depending on them, and specifically as a 
                        directional effect.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A new relation of the concepts C[ause] and E[ffect] 
                        now arises, as soon as we tackle the compositional 
                        synthesis of C and E within the whole process.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Then, seen more broadly, the concentric 
                        forces, A1 and A2, those forces which would like 
                        to lead the spiral movement ad absurdum to a 
                        center point, c, are to be identified as (motion
                        antagonistic) causes; and the motion-rescuing force, 
                        B, is to be identified as a new additional cause; 
                        while, vis-à-vis these causes, the path of the 
                        deflected spiral arrow is only effect (EA1, EA2, and EB).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        One of the first movement exercises that I 
                        will give you after Easter will run something like 
                        this:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Establishment and configuration of the cause of 
                        this effect: 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureP"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Assuming that what I mean has become clear to you, 
                        I will go on from the schematically compositional 
                        arrangement to the configuration of dynamic forces 
                        and wonder: How is, for example, cause A1 to be 
                        configured?
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Schematically, cause A1 has approximately this form: </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig21"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The form of a horn, emerging from a broad base on 
                        the bottom left in order to end like a tip at the 
                        upper right in a point, c. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                       Or, if I unite all the sweeping particles, this 
                        form: 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig22"></figure>
                    <p>
                        For the configuration, this means a development or 
                        increase of energy from the bottom left towards the 
                        top right in a curving arrangement. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In fact, in the representation here, a devel
                        opment or increase of black energy out of the 
                        given, underlying white. A black action out of
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        the surrounding white. When this energy arrangement 
                        is clear, the direction of motion will be so 
                        irrefutable that the arrow symbol can be omitted.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The white given, often seen, is a commonplace 
                        and will be taken in by means of the eye with 
                        little alacrity. As towards what the eye perceives 
                        as contrastingly special, the alacrity of the gaze 
                        increases towards point c. This extraordinary 
                        swelling of energy--or of energic fodder, in 
                        terms of reception--is inescapably related to the 
                        direction.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or to get beyond white-black:
                        Let the given be water; enter fire. Then the case 
                        looks like this:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig23"></figure>
                    <p>
                        or in terms of color: given green, enter red
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig24"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Such a movement is called "heating."
                        The heating arrow coming from the given "cold" looks 
                        like this in tabular form:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig25"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The opposite movement--the prerequisite of 
                        which is the exclamation "Fire!"--is called "cooling."
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig26"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Fire is the given; water entering produces first of 
                        all steam, the water dominates the fire, until the 
                        burnt-out house stands under water.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig27"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig28.1"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Let us touch briefly upon the colored movement between 
                        light and dark:
                        The increase in red. Given lack of red, i.e., very 
                        little red.  
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig28.2"></figure>
                    <p>
                        or, conversely, decrease of red; and all other 
                        possibilities of crescendo and decrescendo. So an 
                        abundance of configurative possibilities lie before us. 
                        One only has to reach out and help oneself, according 
                        to inner need, and the organs of the movement
                        composition are capable of configuration.
                    </p>
                    <p>  The movement-organism, however, that is the </p>
                <pb/>
                    <p>
                        composite (simultaneous) working of the organs 
                        towards a self-sufficient, quiescently dynamic or 
                        dynamically quiescent whole will only be able to 
                        reach its completion when counter-motions respond 
                        to motions or when an infinite-motion solution 
                        ensues.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig29" type="pentimento"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The back-and-forth of the pendulum (p. 117) passes again 
                        before our eyes. This is the dynamic compensation 
                        of errors or sur- <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureQ"></figure></seg>  -pluses of move-
                        ment by means of the antitheses
                        of new errors and surpluses.
                        An extended account of the
                        stable, static analogy of this
                        case is in the chapter on static 
                        equilibrium (p. 37).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In order to reach the centrifugal pendulum 
                        oscillation at last (p. 119), to reach infinite 
                        movement, where the direction of the movement is of 
                        no consequence, I'll omit the arrow for now.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In this way, I obtain a unification of both cases, 
                        heating and cooling. Pathos turns into ethos, which 
                        encompasses forces and counter-forces, united, as 
                        you will see.
                    </p>
                    <p> The arrow in fig. 25 shall thus be omitted. The movement</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        may proceed from left to right or from right to left. 
                        In the process, a center arises, central gray.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig30"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Represented more and more purely, the gray will 
                        become ever smaller, theoretically until it is as 
                        small as a point. For to the left of the gray point, 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureR"></figure>
                    <p>
                        green still predominates and, to the right, red does. 
                        Due to the purification of gray's representation,
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig31"></figure>
                    <p> 
                        the gamut of movement for both green/red and violet/
                        yellow is bent.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If, however, I let the purity of the gray 
                        achieve its completion as a point, then both gamuts
                        will necessarily readjust as diagonals.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_32"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        In this way we have arrived at the ethos of 
                        color, the color circle.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_fig32a"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The arrow is completely finished with, it is 
                        no longer a question of "to over there," but 
                        "everywhere," therefore also "there."
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        Every higher organism is a synthesis of 
                        differences.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>B. Review sessions, summer semester, 1922</p>
                    <p> R1  Monday, May 15, 1922</p>
                    <p>
                        1 My last word: Every more highly developed 
                        organism is a synthesis of differences. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        2 The path to this discovery was analysis, 
                        i.e., the critical treatment of differences (parts), 
                        in themselves and in their relation to each other and 
                        to the whole.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        3 I sought to give a face to the differences, 
                        some kind of meaning that was more than formal. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The practical solutions to the exercises I posed 
                        of course necessarily pertained to form first of all, 
                        as befits our métier. Yet the fundamental idea was to 
                        lend a nature-character to the different components, 
                        so that the composition could find its nature. 
                        Formalism, the new Academy, was thus to be avoided.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        4 At the start of last semester, I began with 
                        the simple, inherently quiescent movement of the 
                        line:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureS"></figure>
                    <p>
                        I then demonstrated with a few examples how one can 
                        "accompany" this "melody" or how one can transcribe 
                        it, so that it spreads out (fills or determines the 
                        plane).
                    </p>
                    <p> Then I fixed the line at several points, </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureT"></figure>
                    <p>and it took on this concise, time-constrained character.</p>
                    <p>
                        Then I took the step towards the first fundamental  
                        difference in form,
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>by leading the line back to its point of departure:</p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>free: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureU"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/> constrained: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureV"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureW"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Here there could be no more talk of elementary linear 
                        effect, since the effect here is the impression of 
                        a plane. The freely circumscribed circular plane and 
                        the time-constrained outline of three- and four-sided 
                        planes.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But they were not elementary planes either, 
                        since such elementary planes are not created by 
                        circumscribing with lines (i.e., by the movement of 
                        points), but by the movement of lines.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>either<seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureX"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>pushed to this effect <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureY"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="left"/>or rotated<seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureZ"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>  to this  <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAA"></figure></seg> effect
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Thus, a construct like this: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAB"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAC"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAD"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        considered in elementary terms is neither line nor 
                        plane but something halfway between. It emerges in a 
                        linear fashion as movement of a point; it ends as the 
                        semblance of a plane.
                    </p>
                    <p> So we have three characters to distinguish:</p>
                    <p>
                        I. a linear one, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAE"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAF"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        II. a medial one, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAG"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAH"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAI"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAJ"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        III. and a planar one <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAK"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAL"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAM"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        where I and III are elementary principal characters, 
                        II an in-between character, a hybrid.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        From the linear standpoint: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAR"></figure></seg> 
                        This <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAN"></figure></seg>
                        character is <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAO"></figure></seg> active      
                        this  <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAP"></figure></seg> medial,
                        and this, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAQ"></figure></seg> passive.
                        I.e., when active, the point 
                        works, and the effect is 
                        linear, corresponding to the 
                        movement of the point;
                        when medial, the move-
                        ment of the point leads via 
                        the detour of the outline to 
                        the impression of a plane;
                        when passive, the line 
                        works in a fundamentally 
                        planar way, and the impres-
                        sion is correspondingly 
                        planar. What can be seen  
                        as linear is a remnant,  
                        is suffered
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        From the planar standpoint:
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAS"></figure></seg>This character 
                        is passive,
                        this, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAT"></figure></seg> medial,
                        and this, <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAU"></figure></seg> active.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAV"></figure></seg> The viewpoints thus stand 
                        diametrically opposed, 
                        meeting only in the medial 
                        zone. Let the following schema 
                        serve as an illustration of this  
                        phenomenon.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAW"></figure>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAX"></figure></seg> 
                        Note. Linguistic analogy
                        active:  I fell: The man felled the tree with an axe.
                        medial:  I fall: The tree fell with the man's last
                        axe-stroke.
                        passive:  I am felled:   The tree lay felled.
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAY"></figure></seg> 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In conclusion the exercise:  Attempts at composition with 
                        these three elements:
                        L and P as clarities
                        M as blurriness 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> R2 Monday, May 22, 1922</p>
                    <p> from p. 136, fig. 22 to p. 140, fig. 29</p>
                    <p>
                        Exercise: a movement of a coloristic or tone
                        value nature with unambiguous direction of motion.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        possibly with counter-motions to achieve a 
                        compositional balance
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (character: pathos, longing thither, with 
                        the desired goal possibly coming hither, or 
                        at least with consoling glances back at the 
                        path already traveled)
                    </p>
                    <p>R3 Monday, June 12, 1922</p>
                    <p>from p. 140, fig. 29 to p. 142 (end)</p>
                    <p> (movement-character: ethos)</p>
                    <p>R4 Monday, June 19, 1922</p>
                    <p> from p. 27 up to p. 37</p>
                    <p>
                        static construction, stable (no configuration of movement)
                        decidedly contrasting on either side
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <table rows="3" cols="3">
                        <head>
