                            </cell>
                        </row>
                    </table>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Color valuation is therefore not fixed, but purely 
                        imaginary. If it is too hot, one longs for green-blue, 
                        if it is too cold, one longs for yellow-red. The demand 
                        can change, taste can change.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Exercise: Organic treatment of two 
                        components, 1) measure/weight and 2) quality
                        Imponderable color qualities go in relation to the 
                        measurable line and weighable qualities of light and 
                        shadow
                    </p>
                    <p> Monday, July 3, 1922 R.6</p>
                    <p>
                        General Review: The organizing of differences into unity, 
                        the uniting of the organs into an organism 
                        was, in manifold variations, time and again 
                        the goal of our theoretical investigations.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        For example: We see human bodies before us, day 
                        in and day out, and see them either as a whole 
                        (simply: a human being) or as an assembly of 
                        head, torso, arm, leg. As a whole it is called 
                        the synthetic view, as an assembly the analytic 
                        view. The end result is the same: in short, the 
                        human being; only the conception is different.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        The advantage to us of the analytical 
                        conception is that it makes parts in themselves and 
                        their interaction discernible. Yet every work is not a 
                        product from the start, not a work that is, but first 
                        and foremost a genesis, a work that becomes! No work 
                        is exactly determined from the start, but every work 
                        begins somewhere with motifs and grows beyond the 
                        organs into an organism.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And even construction, our goal here, is not 
                        already there, but is developed out of external and 
                        internal motifs into its parts and into the whole.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        This is my task here as I have seen it from the beginning 
                        and all the more clearly with the passage of time:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Namely, the transmission of the experience I have  
                        gained in configuration conceptually (drawing and painting),  
                        which revolves around construction, from multiplicities 
                        into unity. I transmit this experience to you partly in 
                        syntheses (i.e., I let you see my work), partly in analyses 
                        (i.e., I break the works down into their essential parts).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I hand them over to you as playthings and give you the 
                        right to break these toys apart to see "how they are made."
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In striving for content and in the effort to avoid 
                        mathematical formalism, for these reasons I offered various 
                        names for the relationship of the parts to one another 
                        and to the way they work together towards a whole, and, in 
                        order to go deeper, I offered concepts of the most diverse 
                        kind as a foundation.
                    </p>
                    <table rows="10" cols="4">
