                    <p>
                        Exercise:  Naturally you do not have to learn this by heart. 
                        Everyone will feel at home somewhere in this table. 
                        Perhaps it will tally with newly emerging work of 
                        your own made by free choice, and then analytical 
                        insights--partly as to form, partly as to content-- 
                        can be given to me about the work now emerging.
                    </p>
                    <p> New example of it here:</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson9_figureAZ"></figure>
                <pb/> 
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson10">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="number10"></figure></seg>C. Winter semester lectures, 1922-23
                    </p>
                    <p> Tuesday, November 28, 1922</p>
                    <p>
                        I will try to tell you a few useful things about colors.  
                        I base my remarks not just on my own thoughts but take up 
                        the thoughts of experts and others without hesitation in 
                        order to transmit these useful things to you. To cite a few 
                        names, I mention Goethe, Philipp Otto Runge, whose Color 
                        Sphere was published in 1810, Delacroix, and Kandinsky (The 
                        Spiritual in Art).
                    </p>
                    <p> Intro. Our task for today is </p>
                    <p>
                        The first part of my task is now to construct a kind <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureA"></figure></seg>
                        of notional paintbox for you, in which the colors receive a 
                        well-founded order, a kind of tool cabinet, if you like.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Nature gives us a wealth of color-stimulations, the 
                        plant world, the animal kingdom, minerals, the composition 
                        that people call "the landscape," all of which gives us 
                        hourly something to think about and be thankful for.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But one phenomenon stands above all these colored 
                        things, as an abstraction of every application, treatment, 
                        and blurring of color, as abstraction in the sense of 
                        colored purity, and that is the phenomenon of the rainbow.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This singular instance of a gamut of the pure colors N
                        occurs significantly not here on the earth but in the 
                        (earthly-cosmic) intermediate realm of the atmosphere and 
                        in consequence has a certain degree of perfection to offer,
                        but even so not the highest since it is merely half
                        otherworldly.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But here, too, our creative faculty enables us to rise 
                        above the imperfection of Seeming and arrive at a synthesis 
                        of the perfection of otherworldly Being.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We assume that what comes to us as Seeming--only with 
                        imperfections, only somewhat--that this might, without 
                        imperfection, be somewhere and that our artistic instinct 
                        must be a help to us in eliciting the form of this Being.
                    </p>
                    <p> What does the imperfection of the rainbow's appearance</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        consist of, then??... From it, people inferred a series 
                        of colors, specifically seven colors with the names
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_figureB"></figure>
                    <p>
                        And the number seven was generally pleasing. There were, 
                        after all, they said in support of this claim, seven 
                        principal pitches in music.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        As strongly as the number seven appealed to me in many  
                        respects, in this case I didn't believe in it. For red-violet  
                        and blue-violet or indigo, as it is called in schoolbooks, 
                        are really rather tiny gradations in the division!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We all know that green, orange, and violet--as 
                        opposed to red, yellow, blue--are on a different level. 
                        (This much I can say in anticipation without spoiling a 
                        surprise later on.) But where to start with red-violet 
                        and blue-violet or indigo??
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First, it is an essential fact that in the rain-
                        bow, the colors appear in a linear representation. One 
                        must not forget that a yellow point marches off in a line 
                        next to a green point, a green one next to a yellow one, 
                        and so forth. 
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig1"></figure>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureC"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureD"></figure></seg>One must not forget that, if we extend and complete the 
                        arc as a circle, then a perfection--a color circle--is not 
                        yet attained, but rather in this way only seven single 
                        colored circles appear, nested in each other.<seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureE"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig2"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Such a linear representation of a plane (so, in this case a re- 
                        presentation of a circular plane or a representation of a circle) 
                        has a snag: a circle formed from a red line is still not a red 
                        circle!
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig3"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Because such a representation of a plane 
                        is, as we saw earlier, merely medial and not active.N This 
                        red or blue or yellow line perhaps conveys the impression 
                        of a plane but is not itself a plane; rather, it remains a 
                        line.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Thus we can calmly designate the rainbow a linear <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureF"></figure></seg> 
                        representation of colors and at the same time an inadequate 
                        representation of colors from which very little can be 
                        gathered--about the oppositional relationship between the 
                        colors really nothing. That is quite clear.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The principal deficiency, however, consists in the 
                        finiteness of this color series. Pure colors are an otherworldly 
                        affair. The mediating atmospheric realm is so good as to convey 
                        them to us--not, however, in their otherworldly form (which 
                        must be of an infinite nature), but in an in-between form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The inconsistency in the two kinds of violet gains in 
                        importance, in interest, when we learn from the scientists 
                        that at its edges the spectrum actually spews out further: 
                        that beyond the red end there is said to be something else 
                        whose effect is heat and that the blue end, too, has its 
                        secret, which is expressed as a chemical effect.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In our rapture and thirst for color we could be tempted 
                        to sense two further, unknown, pure colors, for which our  
                        eyes are not adapted. We do not, however, want to be so daring.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We only want to state quite simply that it is here a 
                        question of half-meaures: the two halves should become a whole, 
                        the violets should become one violet, and the string shall 
                        be tied at its mysterious ends for infinity, endlessness.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="center"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_fig4"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/> And the
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>resultant thing without beginning or end now looks like this:</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig5"></figure>
                    <p>
                        We now no longer need to oscillate as motion from 1 to 
                        7 and, as counter-motion subtituting for infinity, from 
                        7 to 1, seeking hither and thither, striving to get away 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureG"></figure></seg> and returning home., rather <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureH"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig6"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Rather, we leave the human domain of the intermediate 
                        realm, the supra-animal domain of pathos, of striving, 
                        the spiritual-bodily domain that is half-at-rest and 
                        half-set-in-motion:N with the symbol of the triangle, 
                        where the pure colors are only half at home.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureI"></figure></seg> rather, We free our pendulum from the force of gravity, 
                        we let it whirr past, to reach the divine domain, the 
                        soaring domain, the dynamic domain, to the domain of the 
                        mind, of perfected rotation and whole movement, with 
                        the symbol of the circle, where the pure colors are in 
                        reality at home.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        Thus 1 and 7 coincide, and the place in question is called 
                        simply violet.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig7"></figure>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_figureJ"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The cosmic affair of the pure colors has found its fitting 
                        represention in a circle. The appearance, apprehensible on earth,  
                        of pure colors in the rainbow, which was only a reflection of an  
                        initially unknown totality, now formed as a synthesis and related  
                        to the great, otherworldly whole, lies be <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureK"></figure></seg> fore our eyes as a
                        there is now the Color Circle
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        As a result, violet may be observed as the point of 
                        fracture caused by the assault of that power which conversely 
                        humanizes and transforms divine things, to reveal them to us.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        That process would therefore have occurred in such a 
                        way that violence was done to the color circle at violet, 
                        with which the circle tore apart, stretched out and 
                        marched off as a series of color points in the rainbow.
                        (The <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureL"></figure></seg> divine tragedy.)
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig8"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        If we consider more closely the newly obtained form for 
                        representing color, the colored plane of a circle, we 
                        recognize with interest how much more this new form is 
                        capable of expressing the relationships among colors.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First of all, the puzzles of the finite color 
                        series are solved or are no longer worth considering. 
                        There is nothing more to guess about violet in the 
                        gamut arrayed as a row. This new movement, adapted 
                        to an infinite merging of the colors into one 
                        another, has now become a matter of the circle's 
                        circumference, and I would like to call it peripheral 
                        movement.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This is one aspect of the novelty. The other 
                        aspect announces itself to us in the three diameters 
                        with which one can link the six colors and divide, 
                        articulate, them into three color pairs.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        So, on the one hand, movement in a peripheral direction× 
                        and, on the other, movements in a diametrical direction, 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureM"></figure></seg>along the diameters.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        This second aspect of the novelty is so promising 
                        that we do not want to leave it for later. The three 
                        diameters, first of all, link red with green; second, 
                        yellow with violet; and third, blue with orange. 
                        Moreover, all three intersect at a point, the center 
                        of the circle. Surely a deeper meaning underlies this 
                        telling pictorial property of the color order. What 
                        is it?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Experience teaches first of all: If we let red 
                        affect our eye for a prolonged period, this color, 
                        when suddenly withdrawn, has a very strange effect on 
                        the eye--not as red but as green.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or: If we expose our eyes to green for a long 
                        time, then red jumps out instead, as an aftereffect.
                    </p>
                    <p>× along the perimeter of the circle</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        With the same sorcery, yellow and violet alternate, 
                        and blue alternates with orange.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Anyone can establish color pairs in this way and 
                        become convinced of the phenomenon of complementary 
                        colors. try out this afternoon
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        What experience teaches second, we'll  next time 
                        establish in the exercise, specifically, as follows:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_fig9"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        We will divide a long white strip into seven squares 
                        and then  cover six of the squares (with 
                        the exception of square seven) 
                        with thin, pure red watercolor.
                        When this red layer has 
                        dried, we will coat a thin, 
                        pure green watercolor over the 
                        underlying squares on the same 
                        strip (with the exception of square one).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        After these two layers have dried, a reddish square 
                        one and a greenish square seven will appear. In between, 
                        however, will be five colorless squares: two to six.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        We will liven up the somewhat weak effect of both 
                        these first stages combined if we continue the operation, 
                        alternating several times, applying the red from the top 
                        down and the green from the bottom up: first, 5 red 
                        squares from the top and 5 green squares from the bottom; 
                        second, 4 red squares from above and 4 green squares 
                        from below; then only 3 red squares from above and only 
                        3 green squares from below. And so on: ever fewer red 
                        squares (from above) and ever fewer green squares (from below).
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig10"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        This kind of color mixing is called glazing in the 
                        language of painters. It consists of adding separate 
                        batches over time. At every stage something is added. 
                        From left to right always a little less each time, 
                        from right to left always a little more. The result 
                        or, better, the sum remains the same.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Through the gradation of the additions we obtain 
                        the final effect of a precisely graded movement from 
                        completely red to green-red to green or vice versa. 
                    </p>
                    <p> 1 totally red in the first square: 6 parts red no parts green</p>
                    <p> 7 totally green in seventh square: no parts red  6 parts green</p>
                    <p>  4 green-red in fourth square: 3 parts red  3 parts green</p>
                    <p> Between them are 2 red and 2 green gradations: </p>
                    <p> 2 in the 2nd square:  5 parts red  and  1 part  green</p>
                    <p> 3  "    3rd   "   :  4   "   red   "   2 parts green </p>
                    <p> 5  "    5th   "   :  2   "   red   "   4   "   green</p>
                    <p> 6  "    6th   "   :  1  part red   "   5   "   green</p>
                    <p>
                        And experience now teaches us clearly how red and 
                        green come to meet as they decrease, with the weighing 
                        scales balanced in the 4th square as red-green, or gray. 
                        Towards the middle, colorfulness decreases the more the 
                        quantities of red and green approach each other in a 
                        given square. Gray is not operated with directly, and 
                        yet (pure) gray has emerged where the quantities, as 
                        in the 4th square, are equal to each other. This lack 
                        of color at the middle decreases towards the top as 
                        well as towards the bottom: towards the top in favor 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        of increasingly red coloring, towards the bottom in favor 
                        of increasingly green coloring.  
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The reciprocal or correlative red-green gamut 
                        recalls once more, incidentally, our pendulum as motion  
                        and counter-motion.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig11"></figure>
                    <p>
                        It recalls, furthermore, the mobile weighing 
                        scales that finally come to a standstill at the gray 
                        intersection point,
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig12"></figure>
                    <p>
                        though this is not to imply that red and green are 
                        therefore suited to static representation, that on the 
                        left there is only red and on the right only green. 
                        That would not lend the concept of reciprocity a 
                        concise form. Rather, green as well as red must leap 
                        from this side to that. (Configuration!) 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In sum, about the red/green pair I can thus 
                        say: 1. both colors reciprocally give rise to the 
                        other in the eye; 2. between both colors is gray. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In the same way, I could demonstrate to you the 
                        two other diametrically opposed color pairs, namely, 
                        yellow/violet and blue/orange. As an alternative, I will
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        avail myself of yet another, more geometrical visualization, 
                        which on its own is applicable to all three diameters of 
                        the color circle.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig13"></figure>
                    <p>
                        In this case a violet and a yellow base stand opposed. 
                        Above, violet experiences its greatest extension, 
                        whereas yellow is only noticeable as a point on this 
                        base, so that, as far as measurement goes, it is 
                        omissible. Below, yellow experiences its greatest 
                        extension whereas violet is only a point on this yellow 
                        segment. If I now connect this yellow point with this 
                        yellow base, I obtain the yellow triangle; if I connect 
                        this violet point with its violet base opposite, I 
                        obtain the violet triangle. Both triangles thrust into 
                        each other. Each is by itself an expression of the 
                        diminution in its color as it recedes from the base. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Now I divide the two bases into, say, twelve parts 
                        (fig. 14) and can in any one place measure the yellow 
                        and violet content of a segment parallel to the direc- 
                        tion of the base, and the effect will be roughly the
                    </p>
                    <p> × to be verified by measuring segments, where a point = zero</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> same, as earlier in the addition. Namely:</p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig14"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The measurement result for the violet base is 12 parts violet 
                        and no parts yellow. For the yellow base, 12 parts yellow and 
                        no violet. In the middle, 6 parts violet and 6 parts yellow 
                        (therefore gray). Approaching the violet side of the base, 
                        10 parts violet and 2 parts yellow. On the yellow side, 
                        approaching the middle, 8 parts yellow and 4 parts violet.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I can thus also say of the yellow/violet pair: gray 
                        stands between both colors. Experience with blue/orange 
                        would turn out just the same. In practice with these 
                        diametral gradations, it would be best to start out with 
                        a color that appears very pure to us, allow an effective 
                        amount to affect our eyes for an effective length of time,
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        and then, by quickly glancing at white, identify the 
                        matching complementary color; prepare it with the same 
                        intensity; and, by mixing in equal measures in a bowl or 
                        on paper, produce the colorless gray.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If this second criterion for color pairs 
                        failed, we would have to admit, conversely, that that 
                        we had not hit upon the components of gray in pure 
                        complementarity, and we would adjust either the one or 
                        the other component of the pair or, as so often happens, 
                        make a virtue of an error and consciously turn to false 
                        pairs, to enrich ourselves. More on this later.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let us now turn back to our color circle to 
                        express our satisfaction at how promptly the mathematical 
                        essence of the circle meets our efforts at representation.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The radius (which is a half-diameter) cuts 
                        the circumference exactly six times, and, through the 
                        points of intersection corresponding to the six colors, 
                        one can lay the three diameters corresponding to the 
                        three main color pairs, which intersect at the center, 
                        the common gray-point of all color pairs.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Of course, besides these three diameters, 
                        there are as many more diameters as you please, 
                        differing from those already mentioned not in their 
                        correctness but only in their fundamental significance. 
                        The slightest rotation of the diameter about the fixed 
                        gray-point indicates new color pairs that are correct, 
                        only less important.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig15"></figure>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        In such a search for new color pairs, the simultaneity 
                        of motion and counter-motion gradually turns into infinite 
                        movement, and we reach the peripheral color relationships, 
                        where the endless movement annuls the direction of the 
                        arrow, having already been called into question by the 
                        simultaneity of motion and counter-motion.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Let us now turn our diameter to the exact spot 
                        between red and violet, that is to say between yellow and 
                        green, so that we thus identify the new color pair as
                        red-violet  yellow-green
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_fig16"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        The gray effect from this color pair will 
                        have to be composed of red-violet and 
                        yellow-green in equal parts.
                        And red-violet is in turn composed of red and 
                        violet in equal parts;
                        yellow-green is in turn composed of yellow 
                        and green in equal parts.
                        The gray effect is composed of the four 
                        components, red, violet, yellow, and green 
                        in equal parts.
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        How I arrange these four components in order to visualize 
                        them is up to me.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        If I combine them as a cross,
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureN"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        then I recognize in this arrangement, firstly, the already 
                        familiar color pair red/green and, secondly, the equally 
                        familiar color pair yellow/violet. Both, for their part, make 
                        gray, and, in the adding up of 2 grays (nota bene: halves), not 
                        an atom of color is added. The gray effect is proved and thus
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        also the genuineness of the red-violet  yellow-green 
                        color pair.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Algebraically, it looks like this:
                        ½red + ½violet + ½yellow + ½green =(½red+½green)+(½violet+½yellow)=
                        ½ gray  + ½ gray = gray
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        With another rotation of the diameter around the 
                        gray-point, I stumble upon the new color pair,
                        blue-violet  yellow-orange.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig17"></figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson10_figureO"></figure>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        or algebraically:
                        blue + violet + yellow + orange =(blue + orange)+(yellow + violet)= gray
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        A third rotation of the diameter stops, on the one 
                        hand, exactly between the peripheral colors red and orange; 
                        on the other hand, between blue and green, and we have a 
                        new genuine color pair: 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_fig18"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        red-orange  blue-green
                        red, orange, blue, and 
                        green viewed on the cross
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureP"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p> red green = gray   and   blue orange = gray </p>
                    <p>
                        or: 
                        red + orange + blue + green =(red + green)+(blue + orange)= gray
                        The genuineness of three new color pairs is thus proved.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Sum of the peripheral colors = gray        
                        draw the color circle again 
                        (from
                        the end?)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But, as I forewarned earlier, if in terms of pairing 
                        colors we make any kind of error (any misalliance), then 
                        we will immediately encounter a difficulty with the gray 
                        proof. However, it will be good to take a closer look at 
                        the kind of deviation from genuine color pairs, because 
                        it is in no way stated that color composition should be 
                        restricted always to complementary colors.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I cannot, for example, link green with orange dia
                        metrically like this on the color circle, but only with 
                        a segment. Nor will it be possible to arrange the orange 
                        base parallel to the green base; rather, both bases will 
                        soon intersect somewhere.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_fig19"></figure></seg>In reckoning the result of  
                        the mixture of green and or- 
                        ange, I start from the fact 
                        that green stands exactly 
                        between yellow and blue,  
                        and orange exactly between  
                        yellow and red. Therefore,  
                        green + orange = yellow + blue  
                            + 
                        red + yellow.  
                        Thus, I deduce upwards and down,
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson10_figureQ"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        The result of the mixture is not a pure colorless 
                        gray but a yellow-weighted gray, for one thing 
                        because yellow is contained in both green and 
                        orange and because the two bases are not parallel 
                        but intersect in the direction of yellow, tend 
                        towards yellow. The proof of genuineness has failed 
                        in the case of this color pair; thus, green/orange 
                        is not a genuine color pair.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig20"></figure>
                    <p>
                        A new false color pair, as a 
                        glance at the color circle already 
                        indicates, is
                        violet/green
                    </p>
                    <p> For green + violet equals yellow + blue + red + blue </p>
                    <p>
                        green + violet         gray       +  blue
                        yellow + violet  + blue
                        green + violet = yellow + blue + red + blue
                        green + red  + blue
                        gray   +  blue
                    </p>
                    <p> The mixture's sum is a blue-weighted gray; for blue is found in</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        both colors; the violet and the green bases are not 
                        parallel, but tend towards intersection on the blue side.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The third color pair of this kind is
                        violet/orange.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson10_fig21"></figure>
                    <p>
                        For:
                        red + gray
                        (firstly) red + blue + orange
                        violet + orange = red + blue + yellow + red 
                        (secondly) violet + yellow + red (thirdly)
                        gray + red
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The sum is a red-weighted gray. Red is found in both of 
                        the component colors. Both bases, violet and orange, are 
                        not parallel, but tend towards an intersection lying on 
                        the red side.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        I believe this is enough for today. It will 
                        be reinforced, if necessary, in the practical 
                        exercise (in a week's time) and appear more vivid 
                        and expressive to you.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The application can be thought of in various 
                        ways. I myself, in several works over the summer, 
                        have tried out all the partial color actions I 
                        have mentioned, one after another.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It need not disquiet us that these isolated 
                        efforts lack a total effect. We are striving 
                        precisely after just such a totality, and this 
                        again gives rise to new things. Smaller or larger 
                        groups of partial actions, when united, belong to 
                        a greater whole. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I would like to suggest the following, 
                        applied to the Bauhaus--or better yet, to a 
                        Hausbau:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        First: Select the genuine color pairs in graded 
                        sonorities for three separate rooms.N Each single 
                        room would by itself constitute a part of the effect 
                        of the totality, based on red, yellow, and blue. 
                        The certain bias of the single room would then 
                        arouse the longing for new, complementary biases, 
                        which in their treatment of color would fulfill 
                        the longing. The given bias of the single room 
                        would furthermore have the excellent property of 
                        setting us in motion, making us at once enter 
                        the other rooms configured so as to complement 
                        the others. The impression of totality, however, 
                        would then arise if all the rooms were adapted in 
                        the pictorial as well as the actual sense.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        For another occasion, I would suggest: treating 
                        three adjacent rooms, i.e., associated rooms, with 
                        color such that each of them by itself corresponds 
                        in sonority to one of the three false color pairs 
                        mentioned. Then, in the first we would have the 
                        feeling of a yellow load; in the second, the 
                        feeling of a blue load; and in the third, a red 
                        load. These three biases, however, would unite 
                        once again with the "adaptation" of all three 
                        rooms to give the impression of red-yellow-blue 
                        totality.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I take this suggestion from the next lecture in advance 
                        in order to give our theory today a livelier aftertaste. 
                        The story behind the three-color totality mentioned 
                        here remains yet to be consolidated and justified.
                    </p>
                    <p> Tuesday, Dec. 5, Exercise</p>
                    <p>
                        Bring along: 1.  Barely absorbent paper, and [paper] 
                        that takes up water readily N
                        2.  At least two clean bowls
                        3.  The 6 colors of the circumference, 
                        as little opaque as possible 
                        (dried by the oven, coat by coat)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Task:
                        Try out sevenfold graded genuine color pairs accord
                        ing to the instructions on p. 159 (figs. 9 and 10), 
                        in the process of which it is important to hit the 
                        right place according the peripheral dimension and 
                        to measure the quantities correctly in the diametral 
                        sense, i.e., not too blue, not too violet.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        &lt;That means hitting the green corresponding 
                        to the chosen red, etc.&gt;
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>Tuesday, Dec. 12, 1922</p>
                    <p>Exercise</p>
                    <p> Task: Seven-part gradation of false color pairs</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="div_Klee_lesson11">
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="number11"></figure></seg>Tuesday, Dec. 19, 1922
                    </p>
                    <p> 
                        This diametral movement and gradation of colors 
                        that we treated theoretically and practically in the 
                        last meetings has provided us with some fun, I think. 
                        In practical terms, we have discovered quite a lot, 
                        especially regarding the order. We have been able to 
                        assign a place to many in-between tones long familiar 
                        to us. If we did not always succeed in determining 
                        the color pairs exactly, we have at least recognized, 
                        precisely because it was so difficult and because 
                        gray is only one point on a large plane, that the  
                        greatest exactitude is the basis of these relationships. 
                        And specifically in two directions. In the diametral 
                        sense, there arose the difficulty of balancing the 
                        ends with regard to the intensity of the color content. 
                        In the peripheral sense it was a question of deter
                        mining the point, halfway around the circumfer
                        ence, that corresponded to any given point on the 
                        periphery.
                        In ordinary language: not taking too much or too  
                        little of any color and not hitting any false colors.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Optical science may well have to make its way  
                        through these two conditions to furnish experimental 
                        proof of the truth. For us, however, other points 
                        of view apply which relate only partially with the 
                        scientific. And we gain just as much experience if 
                        we miss the mark of precise correctness.
                    </p>
                    <p> <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureA"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureB"></figure></seg> Now Today I shall first move on to peripheral</p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        color movement, to movement that proceeds around the 
                        circumference. This movement is infinite, in contrast 
                        to the pendulum-like movement along the diameter. It 
                        has no endpoints. Not pairings, but rather transitions 
                        continuously follow upon one another. There is no 
                        interruption here, and every beginning becomes an end 
                        again. Unbroken movement prevails over direction (this 
                        clock can run backwards, too), whereas the diametral 
                        movement was only able to rise above direction by 
                        interrupting itself and becoming movement back and 
                        forth.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Nevertheless, a weakly character should not be 
                        imputed to peripheral movement, nor should it be said 
                        that a pronounced articulation is not recognizable 
                        here. The qualitative differences on a short section 
                        of the circumference are already too great.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For example, in the neighborhood of red, the 
                        differences of character between orange and violet are 
                        far too significant.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig1"></figure>
                    <p>
                        And this is the case even though red is contained 
                        in both colors. How enormous the differences will be 
                        between red and another color containing no red!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (For the purposes of today) I will not now ask, 
                        "What is red?" Instead I ask, "What does it not mean?" 
                        That is to say, when does it stop having an effect? 
                        What is its range?
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And we will hardly go wrong if we give its range 
                        the leeway of two thirds of the circumference.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig2"></figure></seg>(red)
                        Last time we saw that it quite  
                        certainly did not mean green, for  
                        red and green annihilate each  
                        other as color.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        But there is however a yellowish red  
                        (so-called warm red), and likewise there is a bluish 
                        red (so-called cool red).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Bluish and yellowish, 
                        however, mean an attenua- 
                        tion in terms of red. So  
                        a diminution in red towards 
                        both sides must be ascertained --or, conversely, an increase in 
                        red from these two sides, towards red.
                        This increase from the two sides leads naturally  
                        to a peak, towards the peak point <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureC"></figure></seg> that culminates 
                        at the height of the red.
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig3"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I can obtain 
                        Therefore I have obtained three points on our 
                        periphery: 1) the red peak point 2) the warm red 
                        endpoint 3) the cool red endpoint.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig4"></figure></seg>Through these three 
                        points the periphery 
                        is divided into a red 
                        stretch measuring two 
                        thirds and a red-free 
                        stretch measuring 
                        one third and lying 
                        opposite the red peak 
                        point.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        can
                        In the same way, I could now consider the blue and 
                        yellow color ranges:
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig5"></figure>
                    <p>
                        brief
                        I shall make matters somewhat (briefer), however, and 
                        simply gather by contemplating the sketches that: 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Blue, as well as yellow and red, has a range 
                        of two thirds on the circumference. The last third, 
                        however, remains free, free of blue, of yellow, or of 
                        red. Indeed, the blue-free third lies between both 
                        the yellow and red peak points, the yellow-free third 
                        between both the blue and red peak points, and the red
                        free third between the blue and yellow peaks. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Every peak, every culmination point, therefore 
                        remains free for a moment from the color influence of 
                        both neighboring peaks.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And thus I can now (not only) say (red is not green, 
                        but also) red is not blue and not yellow, even if it
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        can be bluish or yellowish. In the same way blue can 
                        stretch out towards red and yellow, but never reach 
                        the peaks of these two neighbors. And yellow can tend 
                        towards blue and red, but can never be blue and red.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig6"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This is the illustration of these sentences, as 
                        simple as they are important. (One could call it the 
                        chain of totality.)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Every color begins from its nothing, that is, the 
                        neighboring peak, first quite faintly and then rising to 
                        its own peak, from there to fade away again slowly into 
                        its nothingness, that is, the other neighboring peak. 
                        If I give the naturalistic form to this crescendo and 
                        diminuendo or the ex'act form, it amounts to the same.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig7"></figure>
                    <p>
                        But now something else is added: the colors do not 
                        sound in unison on the circle, as it might seem according 
                        to this chain, but in a kind of three-part polyphony.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig8"></figure></seg>This united representa-
                        tion allows the three-
                        voiced movement to be 
                        recognized and easily 
                        followed in its course. 
                        As in a canon, the
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        voices come in, one after another. At each of the three 
                        main points a voice culminates, another voice comes 
                        softly in and a third dies away.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        One could call this new figure the Canon of <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureD"></figure></seg>
                        Totality. &lt;bottom: what comes now&gt;
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And now, in the same way as last time, I would 
                        like to go on to instructions for practical experiments 
                        and measuring. For this purpose I have to uncoil the 
                        periphery again.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In this unwinding our canon now takes the 
                        following shape, in which the notation of a musical
                        canon also appears.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig9"></figure>
                    <p>
                        The principal strokes stand in the place that signifies 
                        the characteristic of circling, to wit, the entry of 
                        the return or of the repetition.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        &lt;Note: In the oscillation of the color pairs it was different; 
                        we had to return the same way to get back to the starting 
                        point. As script, something like: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureF"></figure></seg> that is, 
                        in a zigzag.
                        Now, however, we are circling onwards, beat by beat. As 
                        script,       
                        like: <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureG"></figure></seg> in a circular screw
                        motion                 
                        Only not in unison but for several voices.&lt;
                    </p>
                    <p> <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureI"></figure></seg>What comes now will remind you at once of my visualization<seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureJ"></figure></seg></p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        black/white 
                        of the red/green relationships, only now it is first 
                        of all about blue and yellow. Next, I will represent 
                        yellow/red and then red/blue in order to reach the 
                        starting point again in this way. Indeed, this time only 
                        in a five-part division.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig10"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This arithmetic table corresponds to the only 
                        satisfactory practical way to represent peripheral 
                        color movement in practice. For if the fact of 
                        increase, culmination, and diminution is not taken into 
                        consideration, one arrives at mixtures that are too 
                        dark in comparison with the principal colors.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        On the left: the plan of operation; in the center: 
                        the calculation of the direct, immediate content; on 
                        the right: the verbal characterization of the mixtures, 
                        the effects of the operation, the indirect content.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Green is thus the indirect or mediate content of blue  
                        and yellow
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        in equal parts; and orange and violet behave analogously 
                        as effects of their respective causes, yellow and red, 
                        and red and blue. We are therefore fully justified in 
                        assigning different ranks to the colors appearing on the 
                        right.   
                    </p>
                    <p> Primary, secondary, etc.</p>
                    <p>
                        The Geometric Representation of the whole process 
                        will show us this even more concisely and clearly.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig11"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Now the eye is immediately struck by the secondary 
                        character of the three mixtures. Their arrangement in the 
                        primary blue-yellow-and-red movement cannot be expressed 
                        more clearly. The causality of the three primary colors 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        is clearly illustrated, as is the dependence of the three 
                        secondary colors, corresponding to the relationship of cause 
                        and effect.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        And now that canon begins to ring out over and above 
                        its notation.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig12"></figure>
                    <p>
                        This is 
                        that drawing that I called      the Canon of Color 
                        Totality. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        It circles around in three parts whose articulation 
                        is determined by the three peak points of the primary 
                        colors. In addition, at these peak points, the onset and 
                        the fading away of the two other primary colors that 
                        do not culminate there take place. Between the three 
                        culminations, however, the secondary colors appear: 
                        there where, waxing and waning--one still culminating, 
                        the other just having entered--both voices meet (where 
                        the value of each is equal); in each section, a 
                        different secondary color.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureL"></figure></seg>
                        In order to represent the inferiority of the 
                        secondary colors in the simplest manner, I can now hold 
                        onto the three culmination points of the primary colors 
                        without the circle, by linking them in another form.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If the pure red at its peak should contain 
                        neither blue nor yellow, should be neither bluish cool 
                        nor yellowish warm, then this can only be true at 
                        one single brief spot, in the sense of the naturally 
                        circling movement nourished by transitional states of 
                        waxing and waning. The behavior is exactly the same
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        at the brief pure spots on the blue and yellow hills. But 
                        the characteristic sign for a brief moment is the point.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig13"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Through the direct connection of the three points 
                        I obtain the equilateral triangle BYR. The sides of 
                        the triangle, in contrast, are not brief moments but 
                        sliding ranges that correspond to the wash character  
                        or differential character of the secondary colors. 
                        I would like to advise you in advance to imagine no 
                        up or down on this triangle. (Otherwise, I would have 
                        stood it securely on a plane.) Place it, rather, lying 
                        flat on the ground. (You will see why next time.)
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If it is lying flat on the ground I can step inside. 
                        If I turn towards R, then I have a figure before me 
                        that is an ex'act representation of the the red hill.
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureM"></figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureN"></figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureO"></figure>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        If I turn towards B, before me stands a pyramid, like 
                        a blue mountain (there really are such mountains), 
                        and, turning toward Y, I see the Gelber Berg, or 
                        Yellow Mountain. In this respect as well the triangle 
                        is a good form. One can reach the peaks of these 
                        mountains from both sides, and two paths lead down 
                        again. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Halfway along the path, however, let us 
                        reflect for a moment that, whether headed uphill or 
                        down, we have now got half of the way behind us.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        At these places on the triangle laid out flat on the 
                        ground, we again find new indifference points there 
                        on the segment of differences--points that divide 
                        the segment into two halves, and points at which the 
                        secondary colors are pure, i.e., which contain both 
                        bordering principal colors in equal parts.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        In this way each of the triangle's sides falls 
                        apart into two halves, into bluish and yellowish, into 
                        yellowish and reddish, and into reddish and bluish 
                        halves.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig14"></figure>
                    <p>
                        With this I gain a new image for the peripheral 
                        movement that, because it represents the perimeter of 
                        a triangle, has the advantage of clearer articulation 
                        into primary and secondary color values. Blue, yellow, 
                        and red are placed in dominant positions; green, orange, 
                        and violet in dependent ones. The triangle has this 
                        advantage over the circle.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureP"></figure></seg>
                        But not only this; it can provide even 
                        clearer information than the circle about the dividing 
                        lines that we called diametral movement. For example, 
                        the red-green bisecting line, seen 
                        as a plumb line, is very instruc- 
                        tive on the green side. This  
                        plumb line hits the green 
                        indifference point.
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig15"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        And this green indifference point is again explained by 
                        the flanking green components, blue and yellow.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_fig16"></figure>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        We therefore have the red-green bisectional  
                        movement, or the complement-movement.
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig17"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        And we have the blue-yellow peripheral  
                        movement, or the component-movement.
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig18"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p> And we hit upon a whole:</p>
                    <p>
                        The red tip hits the green side (complement) and the green 
                        side is flanked by the blue and yellow tips (components).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The yellow tip hits the violet side (complement) and the 
                        violet side is flanked by the red and blue tips (components).
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The blue tip hits the orange side (complement) and the orange 
                        side is flanked by the yellow and red tips (components). 
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureQ"></figure></seg><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig19"></figure></seg>The three complement
                        bisectors (the perpendi- 
                        culars) intersect, 
                        however, at the familiar 
                        gray point.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        NB:  Fixing of the pigments 
                        on the color circle
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureR"></figure></seg>With this I have now finished with flat color 
                        topography, i.e., I have established and explained the 
                        various loci as far as they pertain to the plane.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Before I move on to the spatial, I would to 
                        like to begin to breathe on this plane, I would 
                        like to run free on it!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        There are so many clever people, and there 
                        always have been. And so the Canonical Meaning of 
                        blue yellow red has long been known, a meaning with 
                        reference to the completeness of these three and 
                        with reference to their equilibrium.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        One can say that none of the three voices 
                        should be absent and that there should not be 
                        too much or too little of any of them. This is a 
                        law worth heeding, provided one is on one's guard 
                        against a schematism that will translate the naked 
                        law into the thing.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Such misunderstandings lead to construction for 
                        its own sake. They spew up in the heads of narrow
                        chested asthmatics who give laws instead of works, 
                        who have too little breath in them to grasp that laws 
                        should serve only as a basis for things to bloom; 
                        that one only seeks out laws to test how works
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        deviate from the natural works around us, from 
                        the land, animals, and people, without becoming 
                        unreasonable about it; that laws are merely a common 
                        basis for nature and art.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Thus one can hear statements like: Do not use 
                        gray, only ever use the components of gray, the 
                        complementary colors! Gray is already contained in 
                        them! Gray comes into existence on its own.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Or: Only use the primary colors, blue, yellow, 
                        red, in their most perfect purity! And in their most 
                        perfect equilibrium! For they encompass all the other 
                        colors in themselves! All the other colors come then 
                        into existence on their own.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        These are examples from people who on principle 
                        want to cut capers, a game that one perhaps plays 
                        now and then, when it meets a need, but never on 
                        principle.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        I would like to warn against such rule-bound 
                        impoverishment, and at the same time against a 
                        misunderstanding of my comments up to now.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        For otherwise we could in the end arrive at gray 
                        itself, which, after all, lies at the center of the 
                        whole, on the grounds that in this gray is contained 
                        everything about color: blue, yellow, and red, and 
                        also black and white. The consequence of this truth 
                        in conformity with the law would then be: Are all 
                        colors frowned upon, even black and even white? Only 
                        gray is allowed, indeed, only the one central gray. 
                        The result: gray in a gray world?? No! Even less: the 
                        world as a single gray, as nothing.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        One can, if one wishes, carry simplification to 
                        this absurdity, to its ultimate impoverishment: to the 
                        loss of life!
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        If, on the basis of the dominant importance of the <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureS"></figure></seg>
                        three primary colors, I describe the presence of these 
                        three as the law of totality of the colored plane,
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureT"></figure></seg>then some examples will show how I search for what 
                        fulfills this law and what falls under its sway.
                    </p>
                    <p> formula <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureU"></figure></seg> of a triangle <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureV"></figure></seg> triangle× </p>
                    <p>
                        1) The confusion of the law with the work, of the 
                        foundations with the house, of the formula with the 
                        operation, would be supported by the symbol of the 
                        three points. They are the formula of a triangle.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        2) Yet the triangle itself says much more. The three 
                        sides symbolize the whole color movement that takes 
                        place on these sides, the whole perimeter.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureW"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>
                        3) Complementary movements along the bisecting line 
                        also have a triangular nature in 
                        a certain sense, though somewhat 
                        concealed by the fact that the 
                        secondary color stands in place of 
                        its two complements. A complemen
                        tary movement is therefore quite 
                        close to the totality of color.
                    </p>
                     <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        4) The blue-red movement along part of the  
                        perimeter comprises a subtriangular  
                        symbol. The law of totality is  
                        only two-thirds fulfilled  
                        (two points instead of three)
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureX"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        5) Movement between false color pairs is supratriangular:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/> Total: × flat triangle, spatial:
                        <cb n="right"/><seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureY"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        5a)  green/orange
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureZ"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAA"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAB"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAI"></figure>
                    <p>
                        Green/orange is supratriangular, has one yellow 
                        point too many, hence the yellow load.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        5b)  violet/orange
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAC"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAD"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAE"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Violet/orange is also supratriangular, double
                        triangular, or quadrilateral. This movement 
                        results in one red point too many, hence the 
                        red load.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>
                        5c) green/violet
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAF"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAG"></figure></seg>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAH"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Green/violet is supratriangular, double-triangular, 
                        or quadrilateral. One blue point over the formula 
                        for totality, hence the blue load.
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAL"></figure></seg>These color actions do not always correspond to the 
                        law of totality, as you saw. Sometimes they leave 
                        out one point and sometimes they give one of the 
                        three points too much weight. These last two actions 
                        are not to be described as total but as partial 
                        actions.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Are they therefore to be rejected? 
                        Certainly not. In the sense of totality they are 
                        only in need of expansion, but they are also 
                        capable of expansion. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Time also plays an essential role in 
                        the domain of the pictorial, as I discussed in an 
                        earlier course. Even partial actions take place 
                        in time. So a partial action, if it has had some 
                        success and was well organized as a part, need by 
                        no means be abandoned. <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAM"></figure></seg>One can, a little later, 
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAN"></figure></seg>restore it to totality. One can fetch totality 
                        later, over time, as I recently suggested to you 
                        with the example of the three rooms. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        The two-point partial action blue-red could be 
                        much smaller yet, e.g., only from blue to violet, 
                        and would be quite easily expandable to totality:
                    </p>
                    <figure>
                        <cb n="left"/><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAO"></figure>
                        <cb n="center"/><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAP"></figure>
                        <cb n="right"/><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAQ"></figure>
                    </figure>
                    <p>
                        which, with the the three periods of time 
                        summarized, leads to Total Satisfaction, both as to 
                        number and as to weight.
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_fig20"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        To 3. The complementary partial action would be <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAS"></figure></seg>
                        expanded to totality in this way.
                    </p>
                    <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAR"></figure>
                    <p>
                        To 5. The quadrilateral partial actions I totalize 
                        according to weight
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>Stage I green/orange <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAT"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/>Stage II violet/orange <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAU"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <cb n="left"/>Stage III green/violet <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAV"></figure></seg>
                        or <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAX"></figure></seg>
                        <cb n="right"/> summerized <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAw"></figure></seg>
                    </p>
                <pb/> 
                    <p>
                        <seg><figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAY"></figure></seg>With these few examples I have already gone somewhat 
                        beyond the simple topography of colors. Next time I 
                        will come back to them once more in order to expand 
                        this topography into three dimensions.
                    </p>
                    <p>Perhaps we'll practice in the meantime once again.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <figure xml:id="lesson11_figureAZ"></figure>
                        <figDesc>
                            Totality 
                            Pentahedron
                            I. white
                            II. black
                            1. gray
                            III. yellow
                            IV. red
                            V. blue
                            2. orange
                            3. green
                            4. violet
                        </figDesc>
                    </figure>
                <pb/>
